## **11. Load Balancer returning 502 (Bad Gateway)**

![Image](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize%3Afit%3A1400/1%2AvWzEP89BLDHNGyFam7aWhA.png)

![Image](https://pinggy.io/images/502_bad_gateway_error/502_error.webp)

![Image](https://success.outsystems.com/TK_Resource/07043e9c-b18e-4eaf-8f4b-90f0eaa757b1)

![Image](https://iximiuz.com/reverse-proxy-http-keep-alive-and-502s/tcp-conn-race-cond.png)

### 👉 Meaning:

LB **reached backend**, but backend returned invalid response

### 🔍 Causes:

* Application crashed / not running
* Wrong port (LB → 8080, app → 9090)
* Invalid HTTP response
* Connection reset by backend

### ✅ Fix:

* Check app logs
* Verify port mapping
* Curl instance locally
* Check target group config

---

## **12. Load Balancer returning 503 (Service Unavailable)**

### 👉 Meaning:

LB **has no healthy backend**

### 🔍 Causes:

* All targets unhealthy
* Health check misconfigured
* Instances down

### ✅ Fix:

* Check target group health
* Verify health check path (`/health`)
* Security group blocking health check

---

## **13. Traffic reaching LB but NOT EC2**

### 👉 Meaning:

LB receives request, but **can’t forward to instance**

### 🔍 Root Causes (VERY IMPORTANT):

* ❌ Security Group (LB → EC2 blocked)
* ❌ NACL blocking traffic
* ❌ Wrong target group port
* ❌ Instance not registered

### ✅ Fix approach:

1. Check SG: LB SG → EC2 SG allow
2. Check target group
3. Check subnet/NACL
4. Test with `telnet EC2:port`

